# React Debugging Guide

## Component Not Re-rendering

### Problem
State changes but UI doesn't update.

### Debugging Steps
1. Check if state is mutated directly (don't mutate!)
2. Verify useState/useReducer is used correctly
3. Check if key prop is stable for lists

### Solutions
```tsx
// BAD: Mutating state directly
const [items, setItems] = useState([]);
items.push(newItem);  // Won't trigger re-render!
setItems(items);      // Same reference!

// GOOD: Create new array
setItems([...items, newItem]);
setItems(prev => [...prev, newItem]);

// BAD: Mutating object
const [user, setUser] = useState({ name: '' });
user.name = 'John';  // Won't trigger re-render!
setUser(user);

// GOOD: Create new object
setUser({ ...user, name: 'John' });
setUser(prev => ({ ...prev, name: 'John' }));
```

## useEffect Running Multiple Times

### Debugging Steps
1. Check dependency array
2. Look for object/array dependencies (new reference each render)
3. Check for missing cleanup function

### Solutions
```tsx
// BAD: Object in dependency creates infinite loop
const options = { id: 1 };  // New object every render!
useEffect(() => {
  fetchData(options);
}, [options]);  // Always different!

// GOOD: Use primitive or useMemo
const id = 1;
useEffect(() => {
  fetchData({ id });
}, [id]);

// GOOD: useMemo for objects
const options = useMemo(() => ({ id }), [id]);
useEffect(() => {
  fetchData(options);
}, [options]);

// GOOD: Cleanup function for subscriptions
useEffect(() => {
  const subscription = subscribe();
  return () => subscription.unsubscribe();  // Cleanup!
}, []);
```

# API Integration Debugging

## CORS Errors

### Error
`Access to fetch blocked by CORS policy`

### Debugging Steps
1. Check browser console for specific CORS error
2. Verify backend CORS configuration
3. Check if preflight OPTIONS request succeeds

### Solutions
```python
# FastAPI CORS setup
from fastapi.middleware.cors import CORSMiddleware

app.add_middleware(
    CORSMiddleware,
    allow_origins=[
        "http://localhost:3000",
        "https://yourdomain.com"
    ],
    allow_credentials=True,
    allow_methods=["*"],
    allow_headers=["*"],
    expose_headers=["X-Total-Count"],  # Custom headers
)
```

## Network Request Debugging

### Frontend Debugging
```typescript
// Add request/response logging
const apiClient = axios.create({ baseURL: '/api' });

apiClient.interceptors.request.use((config) => {
  console.log('Request:', config.method?.toUpperCase(), config.url);
  console.log('Headers:', config.headers);
  console.log('Data:', config.data);
  return config;
});

apiClient.interceptors.response.use(
  (response) => {
    console.log('Response:', response.status, response.data);
    return response;
  },
  (error) => {
    console.error('Error:', error.response?.status, error.response?.data);
    return Promise.reject(error);
  }
);
```

### Backend Debugging
```python
# Add request logging middleware
from fastapi import Request
import logging

logger = logging.getLogger(__name__)

@app.middleware("http")
async def log_requests(request: Request, call_next):
    logger.info(f"{request.method} {request.url}")
    logger.info(f"Headers: {dict(request.headers)}")

    response = await call_next(request)

    logger.info(f"Response: {response.status_code}")
    return response
```

## Token/Auth Debugging

```typescript
// Decode JWT to check expiry
function decodeToken(token: string) {
  try {
    const payload = JSON.parse(atob(token.split('.')[1]));
    console.log('Token payload:', payload);
    console.log('Expires:', new Date(payload.exp * 1000));
    console.log('Is expired:', Date.now() > payload.exp * 1000);
    return payload;
  } catch (e) {
    console.error('Invalid token');
    return null;
  }
}
```

# Performance Debugging Guide

## React Performance Issues

### Problem: Slow Renders

### Debugging Steps
1. Use React DevTools Profiler
2. Check for unnecessary re-renders
3. Look for expensive calculations in render

### Solutions
```tsx
// 1. Memoize expensive components
const ExpensiveList = React.memo(({ items }) => {
  return items.map(item => <Item key={item.id} {...item} />);
});

// 2. Memoize expensive calculations
const sortedItems = useMemo(() => {
  return [...items].sort((a, b) => a.name.localeCompare(b.name));
}, [items]);

// 3. Memoize callbacks
const handleClick = useCallback((id: string) => {
  setSelected(id);
}, []);  // Empty deps = stable reference

// 4. Virtualize long lists
import { FixedSizeList } from 'react-window';

const VirtualList = ({ items }) => (
  <FixedSizeList
    height={400}
    width="100%"
    itemCount={items.length}
    itemSize={50}
  >
    {({ index, style }) => (
      <div style={style}>{items[index].name}</div>
    )}
  </FixedSizeList>
);

// 5. Lazy load components
const HeavyComponent = lazy(() => import('./HeavyComponent'));

function App() {
  return (
    <Suspense fallback={<Loading />}>
      <HeavyComponent />
    </Suspense>
  );
}
```

## Database Performance

```python
# 1. Add indexes for frequently queried fields
class User(Base):
    email = Column(String, index=True)  # Add index

# 2. Use eager loading to avoid N+1
result = await db.execute(
    select(User)
    .options(selectinload(User.posts))  # Load posts in one query
    .where(User.id == id)
)

# 3. Use pagination
async def get_users(page: int = 1, limit: int = 20):
    offset = (page - 1) * limit
    result = await db.execute(
        select(User)
        .offset(offset)
        .limit(limit)
    )
    return result.scalars().all()

# 4. Select only needed columns
result = await db.execute(
    select(User.id, User.name, User.email)  # Not select(User)
)
```

# TypeScript Error Debugging

## Type 'X' is not assignable to type 'Y'

### Debugging Steps
1. Hover over variables to see inferred types
2. Check if types match exactly
3. Look for missing properties or wrong types

### Solutions
```typescript
// Problem: Object literal may only specify known properties
interface User {
  id: string;
  name: string;
}

const user: User = {
  id: '1',
  name: 'John',
  age: 30  // Error: 'age' does not exist in type 'User'
};

// Solution 1: Add property to interface
interface User {
  id: string;
  name: string;
  age?: number;  // Optional property
}

// Solution 2: Use type assertion (if you're sure)
const user = {
  id: '1',
  name: 'John',
  age: 30
} as User;

// Solution 3: Index signature for dynamic props
interface User {
  id: string;
  name: string;
  [key: string]: unknown;  // Allow any additional props
}
```

## Cannot find module 'X'

```bash
# 1. Install missing types
npm install -D @types/node @types/react

# 2. Check tsconfig.json paths
{
  "compilerOptions": {
    "baseUrl": ".",
    "paths": {
      "@/*": ["src/*"]
    }
  }
}

# 3. Create declaration file for untyped module
// types/module-name.d.ts
declare module 'untyped-module' {
  export function doSomething(): void;
}
```

## Property does not exist on type 'never'

```typescript
// Problem: TypeScript infers empty array as never[]
const [items, setItems] = useState([]);  // items is never[]
items[0].name;  // Error!

// Solution: Provide type
const [items, setItems] = useState<Item[]>([]);

// Problem: Narrowing not working
function process(value: string | number) {
  if (typeof value === 'string') {
    return value.toUpperCase();  // OK
  }
  // Here value is number
  return value.toFixed(2);  // OK
}
```
